				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\phi {\mathrm{\Sigma }}\mu$$\end{document}) are extracted from the detected voltage as described in Supplementary Note 7. In order to study the effect of background illumination on ϕΣμ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\phi {\mathrm{\Sigma }}\mu$$\end{document}, the sample was exposed to continuous illumination from AM1.5 solar illumination, whereas the conventional TRMC experiment was taking place. The AM1.5 illumination was mixed with that from the pulsed laser using a 90:10 beam splitter. The power density incident on the sample from the AM1.5 solar spectrum was 10 mW/cm2.

